</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/ugemlin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gemlin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Guk Knight</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(5/30/02 10:38:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=654.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire Waiting List?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Just because Verant makes the rules as they are, what counts is how we as players interpret them.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Thats true, but I can remember a time a friend of mine camped his epic mob, and another guild came in wanting it. He engaged the mob, kited him around waiting for a few more people to zone in. The other force petitioned and guess what. THE GM Awarded the mob to the other force, because they were there SECOND but had &quot;SUFFICIENT FORCE&quot; at the time.<br>
<br>
Because of things like that (Even though he got sufficient force to the zone AFTER the other guild, he still lost out to the GM's ruling). This has happened more times than just this case.<br>
<br>
Unless the GM change their attitude, the rules will remain as follows :<br>
<br>
A group of individuals who are in the zone with <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> SUFFICIENT FORCE</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> shall have the mob first, regardless on who aggroed first.<br>
<br>
Example.<br>
<br>
Cleric (a) camping solo for 5 days and rage pops... Calls for help.<br>
<br>
X Guild shows up with their cleric (b) (Has sufficient force) (First in the zone with Sufficient force).<br>
<br>
Cleric (a) petitions.<br>
<br>
GM shows up and WILL AWARD Ragefire to Cleric (b) FIRST because he was in the zone with SUFFICIENT FORCE FIRST.<br>
<br>
-------------<br>
<br>
I'm not saying its right, but it's the rules we must live by. Just like the ruling on camps. There is no such thing as a camp. If you've been sitting waiting for something, a GM WILL Rule that you can NOT monopolize a spawn and therefore you WILL HAVE to share. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/uconnavardosg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ConnavarDOSG</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Guk Knight</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(5/30/02 11:07:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=654.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire Waiting List?</span><hr size=1> Gemlin,<br>
Seeing as you're the strongest advocate of The Rules, I'm directing this reply to you.<br>
<br>
I'm not going to talk about history. Hope that folks don't assume what occurs in the past is always the 'right' way to go forwards.<br>
<br>
Wrt your scenario. The whole point of the list, is that even if the cleric first on the list doesn't have the forces available immediately, what's so wrong with A_guild_01 helping that cleric out with the kill? Kudos to them.<br>
<br>
Is it so bad to help each other out? Or, the fact we play a game means we're bound by what Verant states as law?<br>
<br>
Taking in the bigger picture, yes it's a camp. But it's no ghoul frenzy. No it can't be monopolised, but yes a list can be agreed on.<br>
<br>
As long as everyone commits to helping out (whether it's joining in the fight, or not moving in to take the kill and loot it) those sitting in SF right now and in the future, this will work. <br>
<br>
Cheers<br>
<br>
C.<br>
